HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14 % in new cases
China reports an increase of 14% in the number of citizens infected with HIV/AIDS.
According to health authorities, more than 820 000 people were infected in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018, alone, 40 000 new cases were reported.
Most newly infected people have been sexually transmitted, which is different from past statistics.
Traditionally, HIV infections in some parts of China rapidly spread as a result of infected blood transfusions.
But in this way the number of people infected with HIV has fallen to almost zero, as indicated by the Chinese health authorities at a conference in the Province of Junan.
However, over time, the number of people living with HIV infection and AIDS in China has increased to 100 000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a sensitive issue in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality in China was decriminalized in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT persons is widespread.
As conservative values prevail in the country, 70-90% of men who have sexual relations with men eventually lead women.
The majority of cases of infection with the disease are due to inadequate protective measures during such sexual relations.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to anti-HIV medicines as one of the ways to combat this problem.
