What is the World Citizens' Festival and has it contributed in any way to reducing poverty?
This Saturday, New York City will host the World Citizens' Festival, an annual music event with an impressive number of stars and an equally impressive goal of eradicating poverty in the world.
For the seventh year in the Grand meadow of Central Park, the World Citizens Festival will meet tens of thousands of people who will not only listen to stars such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but will also spread the message about the real goal of the event – to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The World Citizens’ Festival started in 2012. It is a continuation of the Global Anti-Poverty Project – an international mediation group that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting against it.
In order to get a free ticket to the event (unless they wanted to buy a paid VIP ticket), the visitors of the concert had to perform various tasks or actions, such as volunteering, sending an e-mail to the world leader, calling on the phone or otherwise meaningfully helping to raise awareness of their goal of eradicating poverty.
But are the citizens of the world successful in achieving this goal? 12 years to the deadline.
Will the idea to reward people with a free concert really convince them to demand and urge them to act? Maybe this is just another example of what is known as clivivism, fictitious activism – people think that they will really change the situation by signing an online petition or posting an entry on Twitter.
According to the organizers of the World Citizens Festival, since 2011, the movement has registered more than 19 million actions of its sponsors, which promote a wide range of objectives.
They say that, under pressure from these actions, world leaders have announced USD 37 billion in commitments and policy strategies to change the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, this group identified 390 commitments and declarations triggered by the group's actions, of which at least USD 10 billion has already been paid or raised.
The group estimates that almost 649 million people worldwide are already directly affected by the guaranteed funds.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor-executor partnership that "helps children grow up and reveal their full potential". Having received over 4 700 Twitter messages from the world, she promised to give Rwanda US dollars to help solve the problem of malnutrition in the country.
"With the support of the UK Government, sponsors, national governments and such people as you, the world's citizens, we can make social injustice such as malnutrition a thing of the past," said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Nutrition Power, to the audience in London in April 2018.
The group also pointed out that the government announced funding for the "Food Power" project, which would bring about nutrition interventions of 5 million women and children, following 5 000 calls to improve the diet of mothers and children in the United Kingdom.
In reply to one of the FAQs on our website, which asks, "Why do you think we can eradicate extreme poverty?",
The people of the world answer: “This is a long and difficult way, and we will sometimes stumble and fail.
However, like the great movements for human rights and for apartheid, we will win because we are stronger together."
