Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored, as well as who has access to the information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the purpose of Inrupt is to control the world.
“We have to do this now,” he said about the startup.
- It's a historic moment."
The Solid technology-based app allows people to create their own personal online data store (POD).
It may contain lists, to-do lists, calendars, music libraries and other personal or work equipment.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Black and Spotify are available in one browser at the same time.
The personal data online store is unique in that only the user decides who can access the information.
The company calls it personal empowerment through data.
According to John Bruce, CEO of the company, the idea of Inrupt is to provide resources, processes and the necessary skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
Currently, the company consists of T. Berners-Lee, J. Bruce, the security platform purchased by IBM, several programmers hired to work with this project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week onwards, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralised apps using the tools provided on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team do not agree with Facebook or Google about changes that would turn all business models upside down overnight.
"We do not ask for their permission."
In a report published on Saturday by "Media" Berners-Lee says that "Inrupt's mission is to provide trading energy and an ecosystem to protect the durability and quality of the new Solid-based network."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet into a Web Consortium at the Massachusetts University of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has had an influential opinion in the debate on Internet neutrality.
Even working with Inrupt Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I feel a great optimism about this new web era," Berners-Lee added.
