The delivery of the new German military vessel was postponed again
The latest frigate of the German Navy had to start work as early as 2014 and replace the military ships of the Cold War, but, according to the local press, we will not see it until at least next year due to the increasingly perishable systems and the extremely high price.
According to the military representative quoted in the newspaper Die Zeit, Rheinland-Pfalz, the main new frigate ship of Baden-Württemberg class, is now postponed until the first half of 2019.
The ship had to join the navy in 2014, but the fate of this ambitious project was overshadowed by the problems of the ship that had already been delivered.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class commissioned by the Navy in 2007 will replace the ageing Bremen class fregat.
It is believed that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a series of anti-aircraft and anti-aircraft missiles, and certain security technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic footprint.
Another important feature is the longer maintenance intervals, which allow the newest frigates to sail far away from home ports for up to two years.
However, according to Die Zeit, the endless delays in cutting-edge technology mean that military vessels that are supposed to allow Germany to divert military power to overseas territories will become obsolete before they are put into service.
The unsuccessful F125 frigate was placed under the headlines last year when the German Navy formally refused to accept the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the navy returns a ship that has already been delivered to the builder.
The reason for the return is little known, but the German press mentions a number of major software and hardware defects that would have made the ship useless in the military mission.
Deficiencies in the software are particularly important as the Baden-Württemberg class of ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 seafarers, which is half the size of the Bremen class's older Fregats.
In addition, it has proved to be a very heavy ship, which reduces its efficiency and limits the ability of the Navy to introduce various improvements in the future.
It is estimated that 7 000 tonnes of Rheinland-Pfalz are twice as heavy as the class of ships used by the Germans in the Second World War.
The cost of the whole project – alongside perishable technical equipment, including crew training – is also gradually becoming a problem.
It is said to have risen from an initial amount of EUR 2.2 billion to a staggering EUR 3.1 billion ($3.6 billion).
The problems of the latest phregat have become particularly significant following recent warnings that the power of the German Navy is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, Chief of the German Parliament's Defence Committee, acknowledged that the military fleet is actually "in short for the need of usable vessels".
The official stated that problems had developed over time because old ships had already been written off, but there was no way to replace them.
He regretted that none of the Frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the Navy.
National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
A new study carried out in a Scottish highland manor is aimed at revealing how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
Findings are expected to provide new knowledge of the behaviour of unique flying mammals and provide some guidance for future environmental activities.
Researchers of National Trust for Scotland will watch in their research the bats, soprano bats, brown ears and watery mice in the gardens of Wester Roso Inverevo.
Special recorders will be arranged in certain areas of the territory to allow tracking of bat activity throughout the season.
The staff of the National Health Service and volunteers will also carry out mobile tests with handheld detectors.
An expert analysis of all sound recordings will determine the frequency of signals emitted by bats and the type of activity.
A map and report of residential habitats will then be created to help shape a detailed picture of behaviour across the landscape.
“National Trust for Scotland” (NTS) environmental adviser Rob Dewar hopes that the results will reveal which habitat is most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of maintenance work in residential habitats, such as the creation of grasslands, as well as how best to maintain wooded areas in order to be suitable for bats and other associated species.
Over the past century, bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have fallen.
They are threatened by construction and real estate development works that affect hatcheries and destroy habitats.
Windmills and lightning are also a threat, as are flycatchers, some chemicals used to process construction materials, as well as hunting domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, ears rather than eyes help to catch the prey during night hunting.
Bats shall accurately determine the location of insects or obstacles in the flight path by an intricate echolocation method.
The NTS, which is responsible for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the country, is very responsible for bats.
There are ten trained experts who regularly conduct investigations, hatchery inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even created the first and only bat-specific reserve in Scotland in the Thaave Manor in Damfrey and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of Scottish bats live.
Manor overseer David Thompson says that the manor area is ideal for them.
“We have a great place for bats in Threave Manor,” he said.
- We have old buildings, lots of mature trees and great areas to live in.
But we do not know much about bats, so work here and in other places will help you to understand better what they need to flourish."
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before starting maintenance work, as accidental destruction of one hatchery could lead to the death of up to 400 female and juveniles, which could lead to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats shall be protected and shall not be killed, irritated or disturbed, nor shall the destruction of their hatcheries be prohibited.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat guard officer, called on the public to contribute to the rescue of bats.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we don’t even know how many local species are going. ”
